         </div><div type="translation"><head>Translations</head>
         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en" source="#jmr-jbwp-rgg2003">
            <p>There will be a curse from the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit
               if anyone were to bury a stranger here.</p></div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en" resp="#edd">
            <p>There will be a curse from the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit
               if anyone buries a stranger here.</p></div></div>
         
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>Line 1: With anathema we would commonly find the imperative, ἔστω; but Pacho read the alpha of ἔσται; Oliverio saw an uncertain iota.
               <!-- line 1: On this spelling cf. Ch. Michel, s.v anatheme, Cabrol-Leclercq I, col. 1926. -->
               Line 2: The form of the curse is paralleled on a tomb-stone from Beer-Sheba, dated in CE 588,
               <title>SEG</title> 34.1469, available at <title>PHI</title> <ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/320108">320108</ref>.</p>
         </div>
         
